<p align="center">
  <b>First Issue: How to model the Backgammon's elements?</b><br>
  <br><br>
</p>

In other words: Wich data structure should we choose?

<p align="center">
<img src="http://mathias.hadji.etu.perso.luminy.univ-amu.fr/image-echequier.png">
<br>
</p>

In Backgammon, the board contain 24 triangles called "points" and a ridge called "bar" which contain the hit checkers.
Therefore, the board is modelled by a two-dimensional array: T[ i ][ j ]

i : include &isin;

There is a Chessboard :

an array : T[x][y]


x : x= 26, Number of pawns

y : y= 2, The number of the player (0 for White, 1 for Black)

There are White and Black checkers (or pawns) :

BLACK : o

RED : x



